'''''Kalidas Rangalaya''''' is one of [[Bihar]]'s well-known theatres and a center for cultural performances in [[Patna]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/4-day-theatre-fest-opens-at-Kalidas-Rangalaya/articleshow/26441364.cms |title=4-day theatre fest opens at Kalidas Rangalaya - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref> It is in the southeast corner of [[Gandhi Maidan Marg|Gandhi Maidan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100805/jsp/bihar/story_12767616.jsp |title=The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) &#124; Bihar &#124; Kalidas Rangalaya keeps drama alive |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2010-08-05 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref> and is run by the Bihar Art Theater which is the regional centre of [[International Theatre Institute]], UNESCO, Paris.<ref name="about us" />

==History==
Named after [[Kālidāsa]], it was established on 9 October 1974 by Anil Kumar Mukherjee.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/streets-a-stage-for-these-artistes/articleshow/11517748.cms |title=Street's a stage for these artistes - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref> It is built on land given by the [[Government of Bihar]] to Bihar Art Theater to promote and pursue theatrical and cultural activities in the state capital.<ref name="about us" />

==Overview==
Today the Kalidas Rangalaya consists of a stage, auditorium, Bihar Institute of Dramatics office and a cafeteria, known as 'Annapurna'. The complex also houses Shakuntala Janta Theater, Priyambada Children's Theater, Anasuya Art Gallery and Abhyathna Guest House for artists. Classes in dance and music forms, painting, and photography are offered at the complex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://go4patna.com/index.php/patna/34-pi/220-kalidas-rangalaya-patna |title=Kalidas Rangalaya, Patna |publisher=Go4patna.com |date=1961-06-25 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref>

